class Solution {
public:
    ListNode* mergeTwoLists(ListNode* list1, ListNode* list2) {
        ListNode*head = NULL;
        ListNode*temp = NULL;
        if(!list1) return list2;
        if(!list2) return list1;
        if(list1->val <= list2->val){
            head = list1;
            list1 = list1->next;
        }
        else{
            head = list2;
            list2 = list2->next;
        }
        temp = head;
        while(list1!=NULL && list2!=NULL){
            if(list1->val <= list2->val){
                temp->next = list1;
                list1 = list1->next;
            }
            else{
                temp->next = list2;
                list2 = list2->next;
            }
            temp = temp->next;
        }
        if(list1!=NULL) temp->next = list1;
        else temp->next = list2;
        return head;
    }
};


"Idea:
We are given two sorted linked lists, and the goal is to merge them into a single sorted linked list.
The main idea is similar to the merge step of Merge Sort.

First, compare the first nodes of both lists and choose the smaller one as the head of the merged list.
Use a pointer temp to keep track of the last node in the merged list.
Traverse both lists simultaneously while both are non-empty.
At each step, compare list1->val and list2->val, then attach the smaller node to temp->next.
Move the corresponding list pointer forward and also move temp forward.
Once one list becomes empty, attach the remaining part of the other list directly since it is already sorted.
Finally, return head, which points to the merged sorted linked list.
"

#Time Complexity: O(n+m)                                                                      Space Complexity: O(1)
